1
00:02:03,400 --> 00:02:05,920
<i>Sue, right now,
your baby needs to be safe</i>

2
00:02:05,920 --> 00:02:08,354
<i>and you need a bit of support,
don't you?</i>

3
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:11,437
<i>I know you love her. Of course you do.</i>

4
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:15,234
<i>But this will give you a chance
to sort yourself out.</i>

5
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:19,068
<i>I couldn't get on top of it,
with everything...</i>

6
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:24,360
Don't, Margaret. Don't take her.

7
00:02:24,360 --> 00:02:26,120
Do you want to put her down, Sue?

8
00:02:26,120 --> 00:02:27,880
Just put her in the carrycot.

9
00:02:27,880 --> 00:02:29,438
You all right, love?

10
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:32,553
Yeah?

11
00:02:35,960 --> 00:02:37,440
Put her down.

12
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:41,440
There you go.

13
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:43,680
You'll be able to see her tomorrow.

14
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:46,400
I'll take you to her and you'll be able
to see that she's fine.

15
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:48,311
Whoa, darling.

16
00:02:53,360 --> 00:02:54,400
Don't!

17
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:57,120
Don't! Please! Margaret, please!

18
00:02:57,120 --> 00:02:59,350
I'll do better, I will!

19
00:03:08,760 --> 00:03:10,520
The thing I love about this group

20
00:03:10,520 --> 00:03:12,720
is that you don't have to
explain yourself here.

21
00:03:12,720 --> 00:03:14,920
We've all been adopted as kids

22
00:03:14,920 --> 00:03:18,040
and OK, we've all had different
experiences after that,

23
00:03:18,040 --> 00:03:21,237
but it's a big bottom line, isn't it?

24
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:24,590
Anyway, I'm glad to be here tonight.
I don't mind telling you.

25
00:03:24,640 --> 00:03:26,676
I've been getting a lot of grief at work.

26
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:29,473
Things have been getting me down, really.

27
00:03:29,520 --> 00:03:32,512
Been feeling a bit, a bit lonely.

28
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:35,438
You know, when you always think

29
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:38,756
is it because of what happened
when I was a kid?

30
00:03:38,800 --> 00:03:41,792
You know, maybe I'll never be right.

31
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:44,798
But you can't always know that,
can you?

32
00:03:44,840 --> 00:03:47,673
You just... you just always wonder...

33
00:03:57,480 --> 00:03:59,280
Is this where the Triangle Group is?

34
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:01,680
Yes, that's right,
but we've finished for the night.

35
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:03,440
Charlotte. Charlotte Cooper.

36
00:04:03,440 --> 00:04:06,080
Can I have a quick word?
It won't take a minute.

37
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:09,040
Well, what you're looking for
isn't really what this group does.

38
00:04:09,040 --> 00:04:11,320
This is a local support group, really.

39
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:14,840
I might be able to refer you to somebody
who'd be able to offer you counselling.

40
00:04:14,840 --> 00:04:17,200
I don't want counselling.
I want to find out who I am.

41
00:04:17,200 --> 00:04:18,880
Well, this isn't really the way to...

42
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:21,360
I don't even know if my name
and birth date are right.

43
00:04:21,360 --> 00:04:24,680
I remember leaving England -
I was four years old -

44
00:04:24,680 --> 00:04:27,440
I was in a children's home
because my parents were dead.

45
00:04:27,440 --> 00:04:29,840
They sent me in a boat to Australia.

46
00:04:29,840 --> 00:04:32,560
All I know for certain is
I was born in Nottingham.

47
00:04:32,560 --> 00:04:34,640
What do you mean
they put you on a boat?

48
00:04:34,640 --> 00:04:37,280
They put us all on a boat for Oz.
Hundreds of us.

49
00:04:37,280 --> 00:04:39,640
Your adoptive parents were emigrating?

50
00:04:39,640 --> 00:04:41,280
No. No parents, no guardians.

51
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:43,920
Just a couple of hundred kids,
they sent us away.

52
00:04:43,920 --> 00:04:45,960
- That can't be right.
- What do you mean?

53
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:49,240
It's simply not legal. There's no way
a group of unaccompanied children

54
00:04:49,240 --> 00:04:52,277
would be shipped off like that.
- You calling me a liar?

55
00:04:52,320 --> 00:04:53,833
No, of course not.

56
00:04:53,880 --> 00:04:55,836
That is the one thing I know...

57
00:04:55,880 --> 00:04:57,680
I know about who I am.

58
00:04:57,680 --> 00:04:59,400
Don't you tell me that's not true.

59
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:01,000
OK, look. I can see you're upset.

60
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,520
Why don't you come to my office
on another day?

61
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:08,160
Take this. That's my name, that's all I've got to
tell anyone where I've come from.

62
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:10,280
It is 10:30 at night-

63
00:05:10,280 --> 00:05:13,160
I can't find anything else.
I've tried everything.

64
00:05:13,160 --> 00:05:14,680
I've been everywhere.

65
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:17,320
Now, my time's running out.
I'm flying back...

66
00:05:17,320 --> 00:05:21,920
So you have a look, and you write
and tell me how wrong I am.

67
00:05:21,920 --> 00:05:25,037
You come 10,000 miles to find home,
they call you a liar.

68
00:05:27,440 --> 00:05:28,839
Wait.

69
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:34,000
<i>You're not a bloody saint,
You were tired.</i>

70
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,389
Yeah, I know,
but I should have seen it coming.

71
00:05:36,440 --> 00:05:38,396
You can't always see it coming.

72
00:05:38,440 --> 00:05:41,716
- Why's Ben out of bed?
- Oh, hello, miss. Ben spilled his juice.

73
00:05:41,760 --> 00:05:44,991
- It wasn't my fault.
- What are you doing out of bed?

74
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:47,190
I can't sleep. Can I read?

75
00:05:47,240 --> 00:05:50,994
No. Go on, go back up to bed
and I'll come tuck you up in a minute.

76
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:52,996
It's not fair, I'm older than him.

77
00:05:53,040 --> 00:05:55,040
- Happens all the time.
- Come on, up you go.

78
00:05:55,040 --> 00:05:57,720
I just hope I did the right thing.

79
00:05:57,720 --> 00:06:00,360
Margaret, we're social workers.
There's no right thing.

80
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:03,440
There's social-work practice,
court decisions...

81
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:05,360
My professional judgment.

82
00:06:05,360 --> 00:06:08,000
Which means that sometimes
you're doing the right thing,

83
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:09,920
and sometimes
you're oppressing the poor

84
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:12,640
with the middle-class values
of a reactionary government.

85
00:06:12,640 --> 00:06:14,920
Don't make that face at me.
Kiss from Mummy.

86
00:06:14,920 --> 00:06:17,520
Sometimes, you're just tired.

87
00:06:17,520 --> 00:06:19,720
Ooh, you're heavy. Now, then.

88
00:06:23,640 --> 00:06:25,119
Mum?

89
00:06:26,840 --> 00:06:28,240
Mum?

90
00:06:43,560 --> 00:06:45,560
Had bad dream.

91
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:47,720
Oh, sweetie. You OK?

92
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:49,200
What happened?

93
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:52,400
It was a long, long tunnel thing
and I couldn't...

94
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:54,600
You couldn't what?

95
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:57,240
Couldn't get out and I couldn't find you.

96
00:06:57,240 --> 00:06:58,840
Darling, I'm here.

97
00:06:58,840 --> 00:07:00,160
I lost you.

98
00:07:00,160 --> 00:07:02,960
Oh, sweetie. I'm here now.
I'm not going anywhere, OK?

99
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:05,080
All right?

100
00:07:05,080 --> 00:07:06,832
You going to go back to sleep?

101
00:07:09,880 --> 00:07:11,359
All right.

102
00:07:50,920 --> 00:07:54,117
- I think you have to talk about it.
- Exactly.

103
00:07:54,160 --> 00:07:56,196
I only told my husband
just this last year.

104
00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:57,992
Good for you.

105
00:07:58,040 --> 00:07:59,712
What do you think, Nicky?

106
00:07:59,760 --> 00:08:05,160
Um, well, I know what you mean,
but sometimes I think it sounds stupid

107
00:08:05,160 --> 00:08:07,280
if I told everyone
what was bothering me.

108
00:08:07,280 --> 00:08:09,480
What is it?

109
00:08:09,480 --> 00:08:11,600
Um...

110
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,920
It's my brother, my brother Jack.

111
00:08:13,920 --> 00:08:15,600
Uh...

112
00:08:15,600 --> 00:08:17,880
I don't really see him, you see.

113
00:08:17,880 --> 00:08:20,553
Do you want to tell everyone
who Jack is, Nicky?

114
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:24,000
Mmm...

115
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:25,911
Uh, yeah.

116
00:08:36,640 --> 00:08:38,949
- That's my brother, Jack.
- That's lovely.

117
00:08:41,640 --> 00:08:44,000
He found me a few years ago.

118
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,920
Um...

119
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:48,280
Just got a letter out of the blue.

120
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:50,920
'Dear Nicky, I think I may be
your brother Jack.'

121
00:08:50,920 --> 00:08:53,195
And he was.

122
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:56,200
Well, soon as I saw him, I knew.

123
00:08:56,200 --> 00:08:57,680
I mean...

124
00:08:57,680 --> 00:09:00,280
I remembered. That's right.

125
00:09:00,280 --> 00:09:03,200
Once upon a time,
I used to have a brother.

126
00:09:03,200 --> 00:09:05,560
So where is he?

127
00:09:05,560 --> 00:09:08,720
Australia.

128
00:09:08,720 --> 00:09:11,080
Can you believe it?

129
00:09:11,080 --> 00:09:13,640
It was the Sally Army
who found me for him.

130
00:09:13,640 --> 00:09:17,720
They'd taken us both in
and put me in my first foster home

131
00:09:17,720 --> 00:09:19,640
and shipped Jack off to Australia.

132
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:21,680
So, uh...

133
00:09:21,680 --> 00:09:25,480
I mean, I know I have family, I suppose,

134
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:30,474
but he's so far away,
and sometimes it's hard to feel...

135
00:09:35,160 --> 00:09:37,833
Anyway.

136
00:09:38,880 --> 00:09:41,320
So was he adopted
by an Australian family?

137
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:43,629
Uh, no. No.

138
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:45,750
It was just kids, Jack said.

139
00:09:45,800 --> 00:09:49,588
A big ship full of kids from 5 to 13,

140
00:09:49,640 --> 00:09:52,712
all being sent off to Australia.

141
00:09:52,760 --> 00:09:54,910
You never told me that bit, Nicky.

142
00:09:54,960 --> 00:09:58,794
- Didn't I?
- Well, that's what happened.

143
00:10:07,160 --> 00:10:09,400
<i>Could still all be
just coincidence.</i>

144
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:11,231
<i>Do you think so?</i>

145
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:15,720
<i>Well, if children did emigrate
to Australia in any numbers,<i>

146
00:10:15,720 --> 00:10:17,358
<i>there must be some record of them,</i>

147
00:10:32,120 --> 00:10:34,680
I was just wondering
if you had any records

148
00:10:34,680 --> 00:10:36,560
of any unaccompanied children

149
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:39,160
sent to Australia in the 1940s and '50s.

150
00:10:39,160 --> 00:10:41,880
I don't think we ever had those records in
Australia House.

151
00:10:41,880 --> 00:10:44,920
So there were children sent out there?

152
00:10:44,920 --> 00:10:47,400
Um, do you know how many?

153
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:49,840
When? Why were they sent?

154
00:10:49,840 --> 00:10:51,640
I've already told you.

155
00:10:51,640 --> 00:10:53,960
We don't have any more information.

156
00:10:53,960 --> 00:10:55,960
So who would know?

157
00:10:55,960 --> 00:10:58,360
Why don't you ask your own government?

158
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:00,510
They're the ones who sent the kids out there.

159
00:11:01,520 --> 00:11:03,800
I know, I couldn't believe it.

160
00:11:03,800 --> 00:11:06,680
I mean, I was still half thinking
that the story couldn't be true

161
00:11:06,680 --> 00:11:08,240
and he just came out with it.

162
00:11:08,240 --> 00:11:09,958
Yeah.

163
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:12,760
No, no. I think I'm going to...

164
00:11:12,760 --> 00:11:14,760
I think I'm going to still get the later train

165
00:11:14,760 --> 00:11:16,840
and I'm going to try
St. Catherine's House now.

166
00:11:16,840 --> 00:11:19,957
<i>See if I can find Charlotte's birth certificate.</i>

167
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:25,880
<i>If I can get her mother's name off that,</i>

168
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:27,760
<i>then I can probably find out
when she died,</i>

169
00:11:27,760 --> 00:11:30,149
<i>and then when Charlotte
was placed in an orphanage.</i>

170
00:11:32,920 --> 00:11:34,717
<i>we can start to trace her journey.</i>

171
00:11:45,240 --> 00:11:48,550
<i>Maybe get some clues about why Nicky's
brother was sent away as well.</i>

172
00:12:32,560 --> 00:12:34,360
Charlotte's mother wasn't dead.

173
00:12:34,360 --> 00:12:36,720
Lovely to see you, Merv.
How was your day?

174
00:12:36,720 --> 00:12:39,320
Charlotte said
she was in an orphanage in 1950

175
00:12:39,320 --> 00:12:41,000
because both her parents were dead.

176
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:44,200
Well, I found a record of a woman
with her mother's name

177
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:47,280
who got married in Nottingham in 1956,

178
00:12:47,280 --> 00:12:50,920
not dead, very much alive
and eating wedding cake.

179
00:12:50,920 --> 00:12:52,680
Might not be the same woman.

180
00:12:52,680 --> 00:12:54,360
I've ordered up the certificate

181
00:12:54,360 --> 00:12:57,320
but why would Charlotte have been sent
if she wasn't an orphan?

182
00:12:57,320 --> 00:13:01,560
So if her mother was alive in '56,
she might still be alive.

183
00:13:01,560 --> 00:13:04,280
- I know.
- So you going to follow that up?

184
00:13:04,280 --> 00:13:07,909
Well, I'll find the address on the certificate
and follow the trail from there.

185
00:13:30,040 --> 00:13:31,600
Do you think it's her?

186
00:13:31,600 --> 00:13:34,160
About the right age.

187
00:13:39,720 --> 00:13:41,517
Hello, Vera. Yeah, not bad. And you?

188
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:46,438
Is that the time already?

189
00:13:48,480 --> 00:13:49,680
Thanks.

190
00:13:49,680 --> 00:13:51,159
Hang on, I'll finish that up.

191
00:13:57,080 --> 00:13:59,080
Excuse me, are you Vera Wilson?

192
00:13:59,080 --> 00:14:00,640
That's me. How can I help you, love?

193
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:03,960
I was wondering if I could
have a word with you in private.

194
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:06,200
It's something personal.

195
00:14:06,200 --> 00:14:09,000
I'll take you through. What's it about?

196
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:11,195
It's about your family.

197
00:14:14,680 --> 00:14:16,910
Oh, my God.

198
00:14:19,920 --> 00:14:21,640
I knew you'd come one day.

199
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:23,200
It's you, isn't it? You're my baby.

200
00:14:23,200 --> 00:14:26,033
No, Vera, I'm a social worker.

201
00:14:28,520 --> 00:14:30,600
Do you know where our baby is?

202
00:14:30,600 --> 00:14:34,036
Let's go somewhere
where we can talk, in private.

203
00:14:48,600 --> 00:14:50,200
Where is she?

204
00:14:50,200 --> 00:14:52,475
Does she have a family?

205
00:14:54,080 --> 00:14:55,760
Is she happy?

206
00:14:55,760 --> 00:14:58,600
Charlotte's in Australia.

207
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:02,718
She grew up in a children's home
in Australia.

208
00:15:04,400 --> 00:15:06,160
In Australia?

209
00:15:06,160 --> 00:15:09,277
What was she doing over there?

210
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:15,314
What was she doing
in a children's home?

211
00:15:17,360 --> 00:15:19,680
I went back to get her

212
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:21,796
and they told me she'd been adopted.

213
00:15:24,760 --> 00:15:27,040
I went back to get her.

214
00:15:27,040 --> 00:15:30,440
They told me she was better off.

215
00:15:30,440 --> 00:15:32,680
She was in a <i>real</i> family.

216
00:15:32,680 --> 00:15:37,959
What's she doing in a children's home on the
other side of the world?

217
00:16:00,440 --> 00:16:03,080
This flight
is now closed and will depart.

218
00:16:03,080 --> 00:16:04,957
Final call for British Airways...

219
00:16:07,800 --> 00:16:09,640
All right, let me take that.

220
00:16:09,640 --> 00:16:12,040
- How was your flight?
- All right.

221
00:16:12,040 --> 00:16:14,076
We'll go out this way to the car.

222
00:16:15,760 --> 00:16:17,876
You ready for tonight?

223
00:16:31,480 --> 00:16:34,000
That's, uh, my mother.

224
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:35,956
Your grandmother.

225
00:16:37,840 --> 00:16:40,229
She was very strict, you know.

226
00:16:46,920 --> 00:16:50,435
Well, you've got to understand
how things were 40 years ago.

227
00:16:52,160 --> 00:16:55,789
No-one wanted... the shame.

228
00:16:57,400 --> 00:16:59,400
It was such a scandal.

229
00:16:59,400 --> 00:17:02,870
Mother wouldn't have me in the house.

230
00:17:15,400 --> 00:17:18,040
They took my baby away from me
at the hostel

231
00:17:18,040 --> 00:17:22,600
and I tried to visit.

232
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:28,550
And then one day
they said she'd gone.

233
00:17:30,520 --> 00:17:32,317
You had gone.

234
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:40,000
I kept this for you.

235
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:42,036
In case.

236
00:17:44,600 --> 00:17:46,830
Well, I always kept it.

237
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:21,560
<i>I'm up to my eyes at work.</i>

238
00:18:21,600 --> 00:18:23,079
<i>I know.</i>

239
00:18:23,120 --> 00:18:25,076
<i>And we can't afford it.</i>

240
00:18:25,120 --> 00:18:26,758
<i>I know.</i>

241
00:18:26,800 --> 00:18:28,438
<i>And the kids?</i>

242
00:18:28,480 --> 00:18:30,835
<i>We'll be fine here.</i>

243
00:18:59,400 --> 00:19:01,320
Hey.

244
00:19:01,320 --> 00:19:03,800
Oh!

245
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:05,760
- Nice to see you.
- You too.

246
00:19:05,760 --> 00:19:09,040
Uh, Margaret. This is my brother, Jack.

247
00:19:09,040 --> 00:19:11,920
It's very nice to meet you.
I've heard a lot about you.

248
00:19:11,920 --> 00:19:14,360
Good to meet you too.
How was the flight?

249
00:19:14,360 --> 00:19:16,720
Uh, yeah, good.

250
00:19:16,720 --> 00:19:18,392
Get these into the car.

251
00:19:22,160 --> 00:19:23,760
- You all right?
- Yeah.

252
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:26,200
Still OK to come
to the reunion tomorrow?

253
00:19:26,200 --> 00:19:28,960
- Yeah Yeah, of course.
- You must be tired.

254
00:19:28,960 --> 00:19:31,155
Yeah, a little bit.

255
00:19:45,440 --> 00:19:47,960
So we are delighted

256
00:19:47,960 --> 00:19:52,600
to see our usual wonderful turnout
of former Fairbridge residents.

257
00:19:52,600 --> 00:19:56,040
This is a nostalgic and happy day
for all of us.

258
00:19:56,040 --> 00:20:00,113
Now, just before I go,
this is Mrs. Humphreys,

259
00:20:00,160 --> 00:20:02,116
who has come all the way from England

260
00:20:02,160 --> 00:20:05,720
to join one of our old Fairbridgians
at the reunion today.

261
00:20:05,720 --> 00:20:08,473
She'd love to hear any stories
you have about your time here,

262
00:20:08,520 --> 00:20:11,114
so do take the time to talk to her,
if you can.

263
00:20:13,560 --> 00:20:16,200
Hello, my name's Margaret Humphreys.

264
00:20:16,200 --> 00:20:19,200
I was recently contacted by a woman

265
00:20:19,200 --> 00:20:22,200
who was sent here to Australia as a child

266
00:20:22,200 --> 00:20:25,040
and has lost all contact
with her family in England.

267
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:28,510
And I'm here today to see if
any of you are in the same position.

268
00:20:29,640 --> 00:20:32,360
If you want to talk to me,
just come and find me later.

269
00:20:32,360 --> 00:20:33,554
All right. Thank you.

270
00:20:35,760 --> 00:20:39,480
So is this all there is,
the bunkhouses, the farm buildings?

271
00:20:39,480 --> 00:20:41,640
What about the school?

272
00:20:41,640 --> 00:20:46,236
Well, you only got to go to school
if you finished your farm work first.

273
00:20:48,200 --> 00:20:51,556
Jack told me some stories
about this place, didn't you, Jack?

274
00:20:53,480 --> 00:20:55,600
Food was terrible, wasn't it?

275
00:20:55,600 --> 00:20:57,920
What was it you used to have, Jack?

276
00:20:57,920 --> 00:21:01,840
You could always tell the Fairbridge kids

277
00:21:01,840 --> 00:21:05,400
because they were the ones
nicking the other kids' lunch boxes.

278
00:21:05,400 --> 00:21:08,360
Do you know if all the other children

279
00:21:08,360 --> 00:21:10,560
were sent out from Britain, the same as you?

280
00:21:10,560 --> 00:21:12,840
I don't know, I don't know.

281
00:21:12,840 --> 00:21:14,720
Do you know who sent you?

282
00:21:14,720 --> 00:21:18,190
- It's a bit hot. I'll be out by the bus.
- Yeah.

283
00:21:21,520 --> 00:21:22,999
Sorry, Margaret.

284
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:33,160
This woman you were talking about.

285
00:21:33,160 --> 00:21:35,720
- Did you find any family for her?
- Yes.

286
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:41,160
She was told that her mother was dead
but we found her.

287
00:21:41,160 --> 00:21:43,680
- You found her mother?
- Yes.

288
00:21:43,680 --> 00:21:46,440
Do you think I've got a mother?

289
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:48,880
Everybody's got a mother.

290
00:21:48,880 --> 00:21:51,040
- What year?
- What year are we talking about?

291
00:22:08,560 --> 00:22:10,400
Sorry to keep you waiting.

292
00:22:10,400 --> 00:22:12,600
Any records of
who the child migrants were

293
00:22:12,600 --> 00:22:15,831
would be back in the UK
or with local state authorities.

294
00:22:23,240 --> 00:22:24,389
More.

295
00:22:28,760 --> 00:22:30,830
Oh, there's so many of them.

296
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:37,520
These migrations -
were they organised schemes?

297
00:22:37,520 --> 00:22:40,478
I can't tell you, really.
It's not my area, I'm afraid.

298
00:22:42,320 --> 00:22:44,280
So, why have I never heard about it?

299
00:22:44,280 --> 00:22:47,800
Why has no-one ever heard about it?

300
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:50,360
I don't suppose
anyone was really that interested.

301
00:22:52,200 --> 00:22:54,236
Stay there while I get a view of you two.

302
00:22:57,720 --> 00:22:59,199
What's up, Jack?

303
00:23:03,880 --> 00:23:05,871
I can't stand Mother's Day.

304
00:23:11,200 --> 00:23:12,720
Get the same feeling every year,

305
00:23:12,720 --> 00:23:14,800
like someone's twisting a knife
inside me.

306
00:23:14,800 --> 00:23:17,440
So, normally I stay inside on that day
and I draw the blinds

307
00:23:17,440 --> 00:23:18,919
and I let the phone ring.

308
00:23:23,080 --> 00:23:25,640
I was married, you know. I've got three kids.

309
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:29,360
I never knew what was wrong with me.

310
00:23:29,360 --> 00:23:31,600
You know,
I'd think about my mother all the time,

311
00:23:31,600 --> 00:23:33,120
but I could never talk about it.

312
00:23:33,120 --> 00:23:34,600
How can you talk about someone

313
00:23:34,600 --> 00:23:36,591
when you've been told they don't even exist?

314
00:23:38,240 --> 00:23:40,240
I went to see this doctor.

315
00:23:40,240 --> 00:23:43,280
He put me on antidepressants.

316
00:23:43,280 --> 00:23:47,440
That didn't really help, so I saved them up,

317
00:23:47,440 --> 00:23:49,590
I saved them all up and then...

318
00:23:53,680 --> 00:23:55,840
I mean, it wasn't my wife's fault, you know.

319
00:23:55,840 --> 00:23:57,319
There's a...

320
00:23:59,280 --> 00:24:01,316
..there's an emptiness in me.

321
00:24:02,800 --> 00:24:06,080
There always has been and I think...
I thought...

322
00:24:06,080 --> 00:24:10,600
I think that the only thing
that could fill it is her, you know?

323
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:14,036
- Is my mother.
- Jack! Jack!

324
00:24:20,560 --> 00:24:22,360
There's a very strong memory.

325
00:24:22,360 --> 00:24:25,591
I was in the children's home in the UK...
I was only ten.

326
00:24:27,200 --> 00:24:30,560
This man in a suit,
he came to see me and he says,

327
00:24:30,560 --> 00:24:34,040
'How'd you like to go to Australia?
The sun shines every day.

328
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:38,040
You'd live in a white house,
ride a horse to school

329
00:24:38,040 --> 00:24:41,430
and you'd pick oranges off the trees
for your breakfast.'

330
00:24:43,400 --> 00:24:45,120
When I didn't say anything, he says,

331
00:24:45,120 --> 00:24:51,514
'Well, your mother's dead, you know,
so you might as well.'

332
00:24:54,960 --> 00:24:56,520
So...

333
00:24:56,520 --> 00:25:00,600
Now you're telling me that
she might not have been dead, after all.

334
00:25:00,600 --> 00:25:05,000
No, I can't say that, Jack... We just don't know.

335
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:07,960
What we can do is
we can search for her records

336
00:25:07,960 --> 00:25:09,916
and see what we can find.

337
00:25:12,080 --> 00:25:14,360
I don't know. Of course, of course.
I don't know.

338
00:25:14,360 --> 00:25:16,316
You found your sister.

339
00:25:17,560 --> 00:25:20,757
She was so happy to see you, you know.

340
00:25:26,400 --> 00:25:28,152
Nicky trusts you.

341
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:34,950
And I reckon I... I think I should too.

342
00:25:37,560 --> 00:25:39,039
<i>There she is.</i>

343
00:25:42,880 --> 00:25:44,880
Hello, sweetie.

344
00:25:44,880 --> 00:25:46,560
Hello, darling.

345
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:49,440
Good to see you. How was the plane?

346
00:25:49,440 --> 00:25:51,960
It was all right, actually. Come on, guys.

347
00:25:51,960 --> 00:25:54,200
- Did you get any sleep?
- Little bit, yeah.

348
00:25:54,200 --> 00:25:55,474
You all right?

349
00:25:56,480 --> 00:26:01,031
Oh, yeah. I'm tired. I'm exhausted.
But I'm very happy to be home.

350
00:26:24,760 --> 00:26:27,920
That's what I found first.
By then I was desperate.

351
00:26:27,920 --> 00:26:31,400
I've been searching court records,
children's panel, minutes, you name it.

352
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:33,120
No trace of the children anywhere.

353
00:26:33,120 --> 00:26:35,800
I was just looking through newspapers
round about our date

354
00:26:35,800 --> 00:26:37,200
and that leapt out at me.

355
00:26:37,200 --> 00:26:39,160
Now you have
the name of the organisation.

356
00:26:39,160 --> 00:26:41,360
- Fairbridge.
- It wasn't just Fairbridge.

357
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:43,760
All sorts of different charities
ran these schemes.

358
00:26:43,760 --> 00:26:45,880
Churches, Barnardos.

359
00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:48,440
Children from deprived backgrounds,

360
00:26:48,440 --> 00:26:50,476
shipped off for a better life in the colonies.

361
00:26:52,920 --> 00:26:55,600
This is it. This is all fitting together.

362
00:26:55,600 --> 00:26:58,200
The scheme was run from the 19th century

363
00:26:58,200 --> 00:27:00,440
'til - you won't believe this - 1970.

364
00:27:00,440 --> 00:27:03,200
But there was a wave of migrations
to Australia

365
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:05,200
between the mid-'50s and the mid-'60s.

366
00:27:05,200 --> 00:27:06,680
How big? How many kids?

367
00:27:06,680 --> 00:27:09,240
I don't know exactly
but it must've been organised.

368
00:27:09,240 --> 00:27:11,640
I mean, organised at the level of government.

369
00:27:11,640 --> 00:27:16,120
These children were in care.
Local authorities were their guardians.

370
00:27:16,120 --> 00:27:18,600
For so many of them
to be systematically deported,

371
00:27:18,600 --> 00:27:20,440
it must have been government policy.

372
00:27:20,440 --> 00:27:23,680
The Home Secretary would have to consent
to them leaving the country.

373
00:27:23,680 --> 00:27:26,520
The Australian Government
must've wanted to receive them.

374
00:27:26,520 --> 00:27:28,440
White Australia, I suppose.

375
00:27:28,440 --> 00:27:32,280
You're talking about the organised deportation
of children in care.

376
00:27:32,280 --> 00:27:34,480
I don't have any concrete proof yet

377
00:27:34,480 --> 00:27:36,920
but the evidence doesn't
leave much room for doubt.

378
00:27:36,920 --> 00:27:41,000
So, who's taking responsibility for
what happened to these children

379
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:42,911
once they reached Australia?

380
00:27:46,080 --> 00:27:47,560
Oh, Merv.

381
00:27:47,560 --> 00:27:50,920
I've got the names of
hundreds of people in my suitcase,

382
00:27:50,920 --> 00:27:52,640
who all want to know who they are.

383
00:27:52,640 --> 00:27:54,278
I know.

384
00:27:55,440 --> 00:27:57,749
Who do I ask? Where do I start?

385
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:03,920
Are you going to look at all that stuff now?

386
00:28:03,920 --> 00:28:06,280
Jet lag.

387
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:08,600
I thought you said you were working
in the morning.

388
00:28:08,600 --> 00:28:11,034
I've got to. I've been summoned.

389
00:28:12,560 --> 00:28:13,629
Merv?

390
00:28:16,200 --> 00:28:18,840
I'm going to have to get back to Australia.

391
00:28:18,840 --> 00:28:22,879
Well, catch your breath first, eh?

392
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:33,432
We can see you now.

393
00:28:38,880 --> 00:28:41,348
..and sent it to the other department.

394
00:28:42,680 --> 00:28:46,116
Shut the door, please.
To the other department?

395
00:28:48,520 --> 00:28:51,200
OK. Take a seat.

396
00:28:51,200 --> 00:28:52,952
Two weeks?

397
00:28:56,520 --> 00:28:57,794
OK.

398
00:29:00,920 --> 00:29:04,720
Well, as you know, Rita's filled me in
with what you've been up to.

399
00:29:04,720 --> 00:29:05,840
I've read your report.

400
00:29:05,840 --> 00:29:08,520
Look, I just want to say that
I have kept on top of my case load

401
00:29:08,520 --> 00:29:11,360
and I went to Australia in my own time,
that was my annual leave.

402
00:29:11,360 --> 00:29:13,840
- Well, I think that's appalling.
- What? What is?

403
00:29:13,840 --> 00:29:17,160
That you had to use your own holiday
to pursue this.

404
00:29:17,160 --> 00:29:18,720
Oh.

405
00:29:18,720 --> 00:29:21,240
I'm taking this to the social services committee.

406
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:25,756
Tell me. What is it you want to do?

407
00:29:28,240 --> 00:29:32,080
Well, uh, the people that I've met,

408
00:29:32,080 --> 00:29:35,160
they want to find a record of who they are.

409
00:29:35,160 --> 00:29:38,120
They just want to know where they came from.

410
00:29:38,120 --> 00:29:40,880
- What do you need?
- Time.

411
00:29:40,880 --> 00:29:43,160
Time to find their families.

412
00:29:43,160 --> 00:29:45,000
How long?

413
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:46,479
Well... a year?

414
00:29:47,840 --> 00:29:49,600
How about two?

415
00:29:49,600 --> 00:29:53,320
Yes, that would be...

416
00:29:53,320 --> 00:29:55,709
I'll make a recommendation to the committee.

417
00:29:57,280 --> 00:30:03,200
So, are you talking about me
working on this full-time?

418
00:30:03,200 --> 00:30:05,430
That is what you want, isn't it?

419
00:30:07,520 --> 00:30:11,320
Yes Yes, it is.

420
00:30:11,320 --> 00:30:15,720
Now, how are we going to fund you properly?

421
00:30:15,720 --> 00:30:20,040
We're going to have raise your profile
to try and get some public funding

422
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:21,840
and we need donations.

423
00:30:21,840 --> 00:30:24,673
Have you thought about going to the press?

424
00:30:27,600 --> 00:30:28,999
Merv?

425
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:35,958
It's being printed in the papers
in Sydney and Melbourne too.

426
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:47,480
- They're all the same.
- I know.

427
00:30:47,480 --> 00:30:50,120
'Dear Mrs. Humphreys,
I read the article in the paper.

428
00:30:50,120 --> 00:30:51,960
Please could you help me
find my mother?

429
00:30:51,960 --> 00:30:54,758
I was sent to Australia in 1957.
I have no birth certificate.'

430
00:30:57,440 --> 00:30:59,317
I'm in trouble, aren't I?

431
00:31:16,400 --> 00:31:19,278
Have I helped you understand all that, Bob?
It's a lot to take in.

432
00:31:20,600 --> 00:31:22,880
They gave me the wrong name.

433
00:31:22,880 --> 00:31:25,120
They'd given you the wrong name.

434
00:31:25,120 --> 00:31:27,953
That's why it's taking so long
to find your birth certificate.

435
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:33,440
So, which name do I use?

436
00:31:33,440 --> 00:31:35,760
Who am I?

437
00:31:35,760 --> 00:31:37,880
You're the same person.

438
00:31:37,880 --> 00:31:40,640
But I've got the wrong name.

439
00:31:40,640 --> 00:31:44,553
You're using a different name
from the name on your birth certificate.

440
00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:51,600
- Do you want to stop for a minute?
- No. No, I'm good.

441
00:31:51,600 --> 00:31:54,512
So, what next?

442
00:31:55,520 --> 00:32:00,116
Well, what would you like me to do next?

443
00:32:10,160 --> 00:32:13,000
Thank you all very much
for your patience,

444
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:15,195
and I'll be with you as soon as I can.

445
00:32:21,080 --> 00:32:24,280
- I'm very sorry to keep you waiting.
- Not a problem. I'm Dan.

446
00:32:24,280 --> 00:32:25,793
- Dan, please come in.

447
00:32:30,320 --> 00:32:32,480
Oh, I'm Len Connelly. I'm with Dan.

448
00:32:32,480 --> 00:32:34,630
Oh, nice to meet you.

449
00:32:36,320 --> 00:32:38,680
Well, I usually see people on their own, but uh...

450
00:32:38,680 --> 00:32:40,800
I'm moral support.

451
00:32:40,800 --> 00:32:43,320
Right, well, Dan, you'll be fine on your own

452
00:32:43,320 --> 00:32:44,880
but if that's what you want...

453
00:32:44,880 --> 00:32:46,880
- It's all right.
- It's what he wants, yeah.

454
00:32:46,880 --> 00:32:48,950
Well, nice to meet you, Mr. Connelly.

455
00:32:51,120 --> 00:32:54,192
- Uh... right. Shall we?
- Yeah.

456
00:32:57,120 --> 00:33:00,600
So, I reckon if I do have any family,
they might be around Doncaster.

457
00:33:00,600 --> 00:33:02,477
OK, right. Doncaster.

458
00:33:04,680 --> 00:33:07,600
Well, from what you've told me,

459
00:33:07,600 --> 00:33:11,160
I will be able to start to trace
your mother's birth certificate.

460
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:14,520
Oh, I've tried all of that. I've had
the best in the business working on it.

461
00:33:14,520 --> 00:33:15,800
- Len.
- Nothing.

462
00:33:15,800 --> 00:33:18,000
Can't be done. Cost me a few bob too.

463
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:20,120
- Not that I'm short of a few bob...
- Excuse me.

464
00:33:20,120 --> 00:33:22,240
I am trying to listen to Dan.

465
00:33:22,240 --> 00:33:24,560
Well, I reckon you need to see me, as well.

466
00:33:24,560 --> 00:33:27,600
- Were you a child migrant too?
- I've just told you that.

467
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:31,160
Well, I'm sure that tracing your family
is very important to you.

468
00:33:31,160 --> 00:33:34,040
But right now, this is Dan's time.

469
00:33:34,040 --> 00:33:37,400
OK, so there are three possibilities.

470
00:33:37,400 --> 00:33:41,560
We might be able to find
your mother's birth certificate,

471
00:33:41,560 --> 00:33:45,800
and obviously that is what we want
and what we're hoping for.

472
00:33:45,800 --> 00:33:52,200
We might find her and then discover
that she's already passed away.

473
00:33:52,200 --> 00:33:58,440
We might... we might not have any luck.

474
00:33:58,440 --> 00:34:00,320
I'm really sorry.
Excuse me?

475
00:34:00,320 --> 00:34:02,600
What are you doing?

476
00:34:02,600 --> 00:34:04,960
Could you put that down, please?

477
00:34:04,960 --> 00:34:06,800
I was checking what you're up to.

478
00:34:06,800 --> 00:34:10,160
I'm sorry, but if you interrupt again,
I'm going to have to ask you to leave.

479
00:34:10,160 --> 00:34:13,840
When are you going to see me? I've got
documents the detectives found me.

480
00:34:13,840 --> 00:34:15,920
They never found my mother.

481
00:34:15,920 --> 00:34:19,920
Well, if the world's best private detectives
weren't able to trace her,

482
00:34:19,920 --> 00:34:22,200
I'm not really sure what you expect me to do.

483
00:34:22,200 --> 00:34:25,317
Well, I thought you could give it a go.

484
00:34:27,840 --> 00:34:30,920
I'm afraid I have a backlog of people
to see on this trip

485
00:34:30,920 --> 00:34:32,680
and I won't be able to fit you in.

486
00:34:32,680 --> 00:34:34,680
But if you want to send me your documents,

487
00:34:34,680 --> 00:34:36,910
then I'll see what I can do.

488
00:34:39,160 --> 00:34:40,960
Right, now, Dan.

489
00:34:40,960 --> 00:34:45,280
What I'm going to need from you
is any recollections that you have

490
00:34:45,280 --> 00:34:48,397
firstly from your early childhood...

491
00:34:51,720 --> 00:34:55,200
Well, you've certainly caused
quite a stir, Mrs. Humphreys.

492
00:34:55,200 --> 00:34:56,800
There's been a lot of comments

493
00:34:56,800 --> 00:34:59,040
since you broke this story in the newspapers.

494
00:34:59,040 --> 00:35:01,360
Well, I didn't exactly break the story.

495
00:35:01,360 --> 00:35:02,800
People are saying

496
00:35:02,800 --> 00:35:05,280
what happened to
some of these children is an outrage.

497
00:35:05,280 --> 00:35:06,880
Would you care to comment on that?

498
00:35:06,880 --> 00:35:10,360
- Well, I'd say it was, yes.
- That's rather a strong word, though.

499
